520 eV. Structural optimizations were carried out using a conjugate gradient (CG) method without any symmetry constrains until the maximum force on each atom was less than 0.01 eV Å−1. In the electronic band structure calculations, we employed the hybrid functional proposed by Heyd, Scuseria and Ernzerhof (HSE06) [26]. In the HSE06 functional, the PBE exchange term is splitted into a short-range and a long-range part, and 25% of the short-range part is then replaced by a short-range Hartree-Fock term. The Brillouin zone (BZ) integration was sampled on a grid of 11 × 11 × 11 k-points for the unit cells of bulk crystals [27]. The long-range van der Waals interactions were taken into account by using the DFT-D2 method [28]. For the nanosheets, a 2 × 2 slab repeated periodically along the x- and y-directions was employed and a vacuum space up to 20 Å was applied along the z-direction to avoid interaction between neighboring images. A 5 × 5 × 1 k-point grid for structural optimizations, a 9 × 9 × 1 k-point grid for static computation, and a 21 × 21 × 1 k-point grid for the density of states (DOS) calculations were employed in the Brillouin zone integration [27]. The slab model contains three atomic layers with two symmetric terminals. The top two layers were fully relaxed during structural optimizations, while other layers were ﬁxed at the lattice positions of bulk crystals. Spin-polarization was considered in the whole calculations. The kinetic barrier and transition state for H desorption and H2 formation were simulated by using the climbing image nudged elastic band (CNEB) method as implemented in the VASP transition state tools [29,30]. The intermediate images were relaxed until the forces were less than 0.02 eV/Å.
As for the HER in an acid electrolyte (pH = 0), H+ can act as the proton donor, the overall reaction scheme can be written as:

H+ + e− + ∗ ⇌ 1/2H2 ∗ ⇌ 1/2H2 (g) + ∗

(1)

The symbol * represents the catalysts and H* is the H adsorbed on the surface of the catalysts. The free energies of the studied systems can be obtained by using the following equation: ΔG = ΔE + ΔZPE - TΔS, where ΔE, ΔZPE, ΔS are the binding energy, zero-point energy change and entropy diﬀerence. ΔZPE is the zero-point energy diﬀerence between the adsorbed state of the system and the gas-phase state. The reversible hydrogen electrode (RHE) model developed by Nørskov and co-workers was used to obtain the Gibbs reaction free energy of these electrochemical elementary steps [31,32]. In this model, we set up RHE as the reference electrode where the proton-electron pair corresponds to half a hydrogen molecule: μH+ + μe- = 1/2μH2, at conditions of U = 0 V and PH2 = 1 bar.
The chemical potential of each adsorbate is deﬁned as: μ = E + EZPE - T × S, where E is the total energy obtained from DFT calculations, EZPE is zero-point energy correction calculated from vibrational frequencies, and S is the entropy at 298 K taken from the standard tables.
The reaction free energy (ΔGH⁎) and the theoretical overpotential (η) of HER are determined by using the following equations:
ΔGH∗ = μH∗ − 0.5 × μH2 − μ∗
η = −∣ΔGH∗∣/e

