total energies of TiF3 nanosheets with and without H adsorption, EH is the energy of an isolated H atom. The Eb values calculated from our calculations are −2.514 eV (for the T1 site), −1.871 eV (for the T2 site) and 0.485 eV (for the H site), respectively. The T1 site (top of Ti) is the
energetically most preferable for H adsorption. Generally, an obvious
electron-accepting region is commonly found around the H atom, representing a signiﬁcant electron transfer from TiF3 to H, as shown in Fig. 1(b). This is also consistent with the larger electronegativity of H
than that of Ti. The amounts of electron transfer were quantitatively
evaluated by performing Bader charge analysis [45]. About 0.46 elec-
trons transfer from the TiF3 nanosheets to the adsorbed H atom. Generally, the overall HER pathway can be described by a three-
state diagram comprising an initial state H+ + e−, an intermediate adsorbed H*, and a ﬁnal product 1/2H2 (Fig. 2a) [33,46–47]. The Gibbs free-energy of the intermediate state, |ΔGH⁎|, was regarded as a major descriptor of the HER activity. A smaller |ΔGH⁎| means high catalytic activity. The optimal value of |ΔGH⁎| is zero. The well-known highly eﬃcient Pt catalyst has |ΔGH⁎| ≈ 0.09 eV [46] (Fig. 2a). We also

calculated the |ΔGH⁎| of the (111) surface of Pt crystal using the abovementioned strategy and found that it is about 0.12 eV. Notably, the HER overpotentials (η) of Pt-based electrocatalysts measured in experiments are highly dependent on the composition of the catalysts, which are −0.16 V for Pt/Ni3N nanosheets [48], –0.05 V for Pt-Ni/C octahedral [49], –0.052 V for Pt/C [50],–0.022 V for Pt-Ni-Co [50], –0.032 V for Pt/Ni(OH)2 [51], and −0.01 V for Pt/Fe-NF [52]. Our calculations showed that the ΔGH⁎ of TiF3 is only −0.03 eV for the T1 site, which is comparable to those of Pt-based catalysts. The HER free-energy dia-
grams of TiF3 and its analogs are plotted in Fig. 2(a). TiF3 has two types of action sites, T1 and T2. The ΔGH⁎ of T2 site is about −0.55 eV. Notably, WO3 and ReO3 also exhibit high HER catalytic performance with the overpotentials of only −0.05 V and −0.22 V. However, ReO3 is not only as expensive as Pt but also a compound of acute toxicity, and
thus unsuitable for water splitting to produce hydrogen in practical
applications.
We then investigated the HER free-energy diagrams of TiF3, WO3 and ReO3 under diﬀerent H* coverage levels (θ). We considered four

