1.67 Å for TiF3, WO3 and ReO3, respectively. The energy barriers between the initial states and the adsorbing states are determined to be 1.90 eV (TiF3), 3.11 eV (WO3) and 3.89 eV (ReO3), respectively, as shown in Figs. 4 and S6. Notably, the energy barrier of TiF3 is comparable to the values of freestanding carbon-based materials (~2 eV) [16], N-doped graphene on Fe substrate (1.93 eV) [54]. From a thermodynamic point of view, TiF3 provides suitable binding strength for HER catalysis.
4. Conclusions
In summary, we proposed from ﬁrst-principles calculations a new family of electrocatalytic materials with intrinsic porous structures TiF3 and its analogs, for hydrogen evolution reaction. They are predicted to have wonderful HER catalytic performance characterized by low free-energy changes, TiF3 (ΔGH⁎ = −0.03 eV), WO3 (ΔGH⁎ = −0.05 eV). A descriptor based on the d-band center is proposed to reveal the origins of catalytic activity. These theoretical results are expected to oﬀer a vital guidance for the design of high-eﬃcient hydrogen evolution reaction electrocatalysts.
